=== Voicemail

If you receive a voicemail in a language other than English, call a phone interpreter and conference in the voicemail system. You can then play the voicemail for the interpreter.

=== Phone Trees

Phone trees are difficult to navigate with an interpreter. Provide families who use LOE with direct phone numbers which bypass automated menus whenever possible.

=== Troubleshooting
Common issues include:

* This interpreter seems bad. What do I do?
* I speak the language and perceive some translation mistakes. What do I do?
* Why aren't these side conversations being interpreted?

A single solution works for all of them: talk to the interpreter directly about the problem. If this does not resolve it, ask the interpreter to leave and work with a different interpreter via phone or video.

Report problems via the https://centerlink.cchmc.org/forms/interpreter-services/interpreter-complaint-form[Interpreter Complaint Form on CenterLink].

== Written Communication [[written]]

****
icon:hospital[] _Acute/Critical Care_

Consider literacy and health literacy before providing written translations. These needs are documented in the https://cchmc.service-now.com/is?id=kb_article_view&sysparm_article=KB0012321[Learning Assessment].

Translate commonly-used patient- and family-facing forms, resources, education materials into languages that are used by 1% or more of patients seen on the unit.

Provide discharge instructions in the preferred language of each caregiver whenever possible. Follow the https://cchmc.service-now.com/is?id=kb_article_view&sysparm_article=KB0013699[Epic Job Aid]. In the absence of translated discharge instructions, we can:

1. Ask the family to use their smartphone's Voice Recorder app to record the conversation you have with the help of an interpreter. That would allow them to listen back to the instructions at home.

2. Only communicate verbally with help of an interpreter, relying on teach-back to ensure understanding. Provide pen and paper and ask the parent to write down key information.

3. Ask the in-person interpeter to provide written translation of short discharge instructions.

Do not translate progress notes or test results. To provide this in writing to families, summarize them in a letter using words the family can easily understand and request translation of the letter via the https://centerlink.cchmc.org/forms/interpreter-services/written-translation-request[Translation Request Form on CenterLink].

Translation is not currently available for MyChart messaging, text messages, and emails to families. If you receive a message in a language other than English, request a translation from the https://centerlink.cchmc.org/forms/interpreter-services/written-translation-request[Translation Request Form on CenterLink].
****

****
icon:store[] _Ambulatory_

When providing any documents to someone who sometimes uses a language other than English, ask the person what language(s) they would like the particular documents in.

Consider assessing health literacy by asking a question such as:

   * "How confident are you filling out medical forms by yourself?”
   * "How often do you have problems learning about your medical condition because of difficulty with written information?"

Translate commonly-used patient- and family-facing forms, resources, https://centerlink.cchmc.org/patient-services/patient-and-family-education/home[education materials] into languages that are used by 1% or more of patients seen in the clinic.

